w that the North Columbus WRF has the necessary equipment and the operating and training procedures required for the safe operation of the chlorination system.  During the most recent hazard review, the hazard review team made the following recommendations for improving the safe operating procedures and for minimizing the likelihood of an offsite release from the chlorination system:

New Recommendations from the safety Inspection of the NCWRF on 5 June 2009: 
1. Require annual third party inspections of all ton cylinder hoists;
2. Require The North plant, transition over to a post and yoke for ton cylinder attachment from a threaded pigtail.  
3. Require all operators and managed maintenance should have training on the new CI pamphlet 155. 
4. Require all new operators a training session on operation of the hoists, who lift ton cylinders of chlorine or sulfur dioxide. 
5. Require sniff test of all ton chlorine cylinders valves being delivered and a log kept of defects to monitor quality of the chlorine cylinders.  

The below items have been completed after the June 21, 2004 submission:
1. Require personnel entering the chlorine building to carry a mouth-bit escape respirator and chemical safety goggles while in the building;
2. Require operators to complete crane operator training before transferring one-ton containers using the hoist system;
3. Require hoist inspections that follow ANSI and OSHA guidelines;
4. Require operators and maintenance employees to complete the Chlorine Institute Training Program, "Safe Handling of Chlorine";
5. Install a protective rail and truck barrier posts to protect the manifold from swinging one-ton containers during unloading; and
6. Require a hot work permit system for any cutting and welding inside the chlorine building.
